ctivity in the region, and is a leading light in the Global Counter-Terrorism Forum’s work on the Sahel. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Western Balkans</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he UK and US share a common strategic interest in stability in the Western Balkans.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> We continue to work closely together, particularly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by supporting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">all countries in the region on the path to NATO and EU membership.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK and US are firm supporters of an independent, stable Kosovo, and the US provides powerful political support for the EU-facilitated Dialogue between Kosovo and Serbia.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Across the region, US funding complements UK bilateral spending to support necessary reforms and capacity building.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 1.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Emerging Powers </span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The U</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">K and U</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S share </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a broad</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> analysis about the way the world is changing. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Like us, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the US </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are actively seeking to deepen and broaden their relationships with the leading powers of the future. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This presents us with opportunities to work together in the many areas where our interests overlap, in the US a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in third countries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> themselves</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our discussions with the US are part of a wider plan of engagement with traditional allies on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es to the E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">merging </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">owers, both to share best practice and identify areas where we might work together to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">achieve </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">specific results. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> As well as our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dialogue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with the US, w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e already have a Ministerial process underway with Australia and Canada, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">official level discussions with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> France and Germany.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The British Embassy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Washington has launched a series of policy discussions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> working in conjunction with the German </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Embassy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These bring together UK and US policy makers alongside future leaders from the cadre of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">merging </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ower diplomats based in the US to discuss the challenges and opportunities presented by the rise of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">merging </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">owers and the changing international landscape. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The purpose is to strengthen the UK’s relationships with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">merging </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">owers, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reinforcing efforts in capitals,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> identify areas for further UK-US cooperation in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">merging </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Powers,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and provide new perspectives and ideas on how to operate in tomorrow’s world. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">discussions will continue throughout the autumn and consider </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">important</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> areas such as international security, the global economy and people-to-people links.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Asia Rebalance</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The US ‘Rebalance’ (or ‘Pivot’), first announced in October 2011</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by the then Secretary of State Hillary Clinton</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, involves “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">strengthening bilateral security alliances; deepening working relationships with emerging powers; engaging with regional multilateral institutions; expanding trade and investment; forging a broad-based military presence; and advancing democracy and human rights</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">." </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This has been brought out in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">President </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Obama’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">commitment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to attend</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> every East Asia Summit meeting,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> US efforts to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">conclude the Trans-Pacific Partnership,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">increased </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">US </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">military presence in the region</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> including the stationing of 2500 US marines in Australia and shifting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">60% of US nava</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l assets to the Pacific by 2020,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">renewed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">US </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">focus on South-East Asia including an increase in high-level visits and the establishment of official level bilateral </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dialogues</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="46" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> also</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> looked to increase its relationships outside the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ransatlantic area, whilst still maintaining the current UK-US relationship. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The FCO has refocused its diplomatic resources towards the Asia region to strengthen our presence and build durable and wide-ranging bilateral relationships with the Emerging Powers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in the Asia region.  For example, we have:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 55.2pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e-opened our Embassy in Laos; </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 55.2pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ecruited over 100 new staff in our missions across the region; </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 55.2pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">einforced our Asia teams in Washington and Brussels; </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 55.2pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ncreased by 50% the number of diplomats in our China network who speak Chinese.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There has also been a significant increase in UK ministerial visits to the region and we have encouraged closer EU-US engagement on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Asia</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="47" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">An important aspect of the Asia Rebalance is the development of the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP), a free trade agreement being negotiated by 12 Asia Pacific countries, including the US.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The size and scope of the TPP mark it out in terms of both economic and strategic implications.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> In common with the T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ransatlantic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rade and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nvestment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">artnership (TTIP)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the reduction of non-tariff barriers will provide greater economic benefits than reduction in tariffs alone.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Increased regulatory coherence will be central to both agreements and will provide significan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t positive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">spillover</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> effects.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While the two agreements are separate, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">we expect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> there will be read across </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">between them, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with the US playing a critical role.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> In his speech to the World Affairs Council in Los Angeles, the Foreign Secretary said, “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">[T]he impact from reduced tariffs will be even greater if we can ensure that the Trans-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Atlantic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">and Trans-Pacific partnerships are mutually reinforcing.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> Together they can form the basis for a radical reinvigoration of the global trade agenda, offering a once-in-a-generation opportunity to rebuild trust in trade and investment as the engine for job creation and economic growth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">”</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="48" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK welcomes the recent shift in the US focus to Asia, which is in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">line with our own shift</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in resources</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> towards the Emerging Powers.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The US rebalance towards Asia was perceived by some as a disengagement from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">traditional areas of focus such as Europe </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Middle East.  But th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e latter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> region continues to occupy significant US time and attention, and this has not been diminished by their increased focus on Asia</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e do not see the shift as a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> disengagement from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Europe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> but as a move that is in direct support of our interests. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="49" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In fact, we aim to capitalise on renewed US engagement to further our own major secu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rity and economic interests in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Asia.  We are working increasingly closely with the US in policy areas relevant to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Asia where we have common aims.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n cyber security, the South China Sea and North Korea, on Burma, in the Pacific, and on getting China to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">commit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to rules on transparency and good governance, corruption, intellectual property and open markets.  We have regular UK-US </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">discussions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> at working and ministerial level on Asia and our missions in the region work closely together, coordinating on policy and sharing best practice. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For example, in Burma the UK and US jointly called for humanitarian action ahead of the possible Cyclone </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Mahasen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in June which resulted in the re-housing of 60,000 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Rohingya</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; and USAID and D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ID contribute to the Livelihoods and Food Security Trust Fund in Burma. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">worked on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">collaborative projects on the ground in the Pacific, including jointly donating a solar desalination system to the Government of Tuvalu in 2011. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Working </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ogether in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">nternational </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">nstitutions</span></p><ol start="50" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK and US work together closely throughout the UN system on a wide range of security, development and human rights issues. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The UK and US are important partners</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on all work in the United Nations Security Council. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As a fellow member of the P5 group of permanent members of the Council, we coor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dinate positions at every level.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="51" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As two of the major contributors to UN budgets, we have a common interest in ensuring that the UN provides value for taxpayers’ money.  The UK and the US work together closely on this in the UN General Assembly and across the wider UN system, in cooperation with other like-minded countries. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The UK and US are co-c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hairs of the Geneva Group, an informal group of sixteen of the major financial contributor countries to the UN created in 1964.  The Geneva Group works across the UN system to encourage international insti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tutional reform with a focus on management reform, budgetary discipline,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> encouraging sound human resources,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> audit and accounting practices,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and monitoring capital projects. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="52" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK worked closely with the US on the Arms Trade Treaty (ATT), to encourage </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">US</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> engagement and support as one of the major exporters of conventional arms and as a country with a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">robust</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> export control system. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Despite initial concerns, the US was a firm supporter of the ATT by the end of the negotiations in April 2013.  Not only did it vote in favour of the adoption, it also co-sponsored the resolution to put the ATT to UN</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eneral </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ssembly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> after Syria, Iran and the DPRK blocked it. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK will continue to work with the US to support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">strong</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and transparent implementation of the ATT.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="53" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">During the UK Presidency of the G8 in 2013, the close relationship and shared objectives with the United States helped with achieving ambitious outcomes in this forum.  The US was very supportive of the Transparency element of the G8 3T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agenda, vocally backing the UK’s proposals in G8 discussions at official and political level.   On implementation of the Extractives Industry Transparency Initiative and mandatory reporting requirements for extractives companies, the US helped set the pace with its own domestic policy and legislation, providing a positive case study for other G8 members to learn from.   With a strong push by the UK and support from the US, both in formal meetings and behind the scenes, the G8 was able to agree ambitious </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">commitments</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to greater transparency in the extractive sector.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="54" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The G8 made a clear </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">commitment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to break down barriers to trade at home and abroad by resisting protectionism and finalising a set of ambitious trade deals.  As part of this, the US and UK worked closely on plans to begin negotiations for the Transatlantic Trade and Investment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Partnership which was launched a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t Lough Erne.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This is covered further below.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="55" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Within the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">G20</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> there is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> excellent contact between </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the UK and US </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Sherpa offices. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> notable recent example of co-operation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">our work with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the US, and other G7 partners</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to release a statement calming “currency wars” tensions in financial markets </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> February 2013 (later adopted by G20 Finance Ministers). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We also worked earlier this year with the US to obtain G20 consensus on fiscal policy, agreeing that G20 countries should set out strategies for medium-term fiscal consolidation.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Overseas Territories</span></p><ol start="56" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK’s Overseas Territories (OTs) are an important asset in our strategic partnership with the United States.  The OTs provide occasional logistical and other support to U</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> forces.  Two of them – Ascension and the British Indian Ocean Territory (Diego Garcia) – host substantial and long-standing US military bases.  Given the strategic significance of some of the OTs, these arrangements with the US constitute an important UK contribution to the bilateral defence relationship (dis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cussed below).  The OTs also co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">operate with the US in other respects.  In the Caribbean, for example, law enforcement authorities from the Overseas Territories, UK and US work closely on regional drugs and international crime issues.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The agreement with the US on Diego Garcia expires in December 2016, though there is a provision to extend it for a further twenty years if both parties agree.  Recognising the importance of the Diego Garcia facility to our shared strategic interests, the Government supports a continuation of the US presence in BIOT.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are currently discussing this with the United States but the details of any agreement will be finalised after the current review of our policy towards resettlement of BIOT has concluded.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Defence Relationship</span></p><ol start="58" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The defence relationship has for decades been one of the foundati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ons of the broader bilateral UK-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">US relationship. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our strategies, policies and plans have been well aligned.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and US forces are now more interoperable than ever, and we have worked effectively together to find solutions to the challenges of the current operational environment.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Other staples of the defence relationship have continued to flourish during this period, notably cooperation on Nuclear, Carrier Strike, J</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oint </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">trike </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ighter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Science &amp; Technology, amongst others. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are focused on sustaining the close bilateral defence relationship as we plan the drawdown in Afghanistan, just as within the NATO Alliance more generally.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="59" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The US ‘Strategic Guidance’ published in January 2012 provided the policy rationale for the reduction in the defence budget of half a trillion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> dollars over the next decade.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This guidance included a change to US defence planning assumptions and also re-emphas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ised the Middle East and Asia </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Pacific as the US’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> top strategic priorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The US will look to replac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e protracted land-based stabilis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ation operations with stealth, precision and stand-off operations whenever possible. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The emphasis on high end capabilities is about deterrence and power projection rather than intervention.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The President’s defence budget request for FY14 (Oct 13-Sep 14) asked for $526</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">illion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for the Department of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Defense</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (DOD) base budget (a small reduction from previous plans) and $80</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">illio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n for current operations.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As the budget sequester </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">came into effect during 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">we expect to see further substantial reductions in defence expenditure over the next 10 years; the full sequester level budgetary caps would foresee the DOD face an approximate $52 billion cut to the 2014 Defence budget.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 19.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="60" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Secretary of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Defense</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Chuck </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hagel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> continues to direct the DOD to examine opportunities to engage with allies (especially, but not exclusively, the UK) on the management of financial pressures and the changing global environment. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With the publishing of our International Defence Engagement Strategy (jointly signed by both the Defence Secretary and Foreign Secretary) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">we are seeking </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">opportunities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">work together</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in line with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Secretary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hagel’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">plan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This strand has been protected even when the D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">OD </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">considered what lesser priorities needed to be dropped</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as a result of the sequester.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">MOD</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will engage and lobby for the US </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to remain outward looking </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the light of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> budget pressures and to protect UK interests in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">next Quadrennial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Defense</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Defence Sales to the US</span></p><ol start="61" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We continue </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">promote</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Defence Exports to the US </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">prosperity.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he balance of trade </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">currently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">favours the US defence industry by a factor of 2:1 - $2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> billion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> exports to the UK per annum compared to about $1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> billion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to the US</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> There are a number of capabilities and platforms well suited to meet US requirements and we will continue to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">promote</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> them</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> along with the Defence Trade Cooperation Treaty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Its purpose is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to remove some of the obstacles to defence exports, to help British companies export into the US, and to encourage US investment in the UK.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 19.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ITAR</span></p><ol start="62" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ITAR (International Traffic in Arms Regulations) is the set of rules by which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">US governs export of its defence equipment and technology. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">US</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> requires recipients to sign up to their regulations before an export is approved and whenever, once exported, items are re-expo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rted. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Approval often requires C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ongressional notification. This does not prevent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK obtaining equipment, but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">can add</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> significant delays, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">affect our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ability to manage our supply chain efficiently</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> increas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> uncertainty </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">defence sale</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> incorporating US items or information.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he likely </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">impact </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and additional burden of ITAR on MOD’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">intention</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to introduce the private sector into the Acquisition and Support functions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is currently being assessed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Partnerships with the US</span></p><ol start="63" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have continued to see good </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">progress</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in stepping up UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">US defence collaboration on major projects and programmes.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> HMS Vigilant conducted a successful Demonstration and Shakedown Operation (DASO) in October, and the US is making significant investment to ensure that the UK’s Successor programme can be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">completed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on time.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> We have taken delivery of a second </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Standard Take-off and Vertical Landing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">STOVL</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> J</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oint </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">trike </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ighter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and have our first two pilots in conversion training at Eglin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Air Force Base</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, along wi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">th the associated ground crew.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There has also been good </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">progress</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">strands of the UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">US Carrier Operations Statement of Intent. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Army has strengthened its institutional and formation-level ties, explored cost-avoiding opportunities to share training environments, formation-level interoperability, combined training and upstream activity. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have also developed still stronger ties on Personnel issues. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Science and Technology collaboration continue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to develop. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">NATO</span></p><ol start="64" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">NATO is one of our primary vehicles for defence and s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ecurity cooperation with the US</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The political weight and deterrent effect that NATO carries as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">result of this Transatlantic bond cannot be overstated.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> In practical terms, NATO brings continued military interoperability with the US and a unified Command Structure, which have demonstrated their importance in operations such as Afghanistan and Libya. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The US are clear that its European Alliances are unique and that it will remain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">committed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to NATO.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> But the changing nature of threats and broader strategic environment have contributed to heightened calls from the US for Europe to make a greater contribution to security.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Given our unique relationship, we continue to work closely with the US to ensure they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">understand the European context. We also work closely with European partners so they appreciate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the need to step up to their responsibilities as part of the effort to keep the US – including the US public – assured of the value of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">commitment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to Europe.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Nuclear Cooperation</span></p><ol start="65" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The 1958 Mutual Defence Agreement and the 1963 Polaris Sales Agreement provide the framework for an extensive programme of UK-US cooperation on nuclear deterrence.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This includes co-operation on missiles, warheads, and submarines, including on naval nuclear propulsion and a common missile compartment. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">All such cooperation is in compliance with the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty and exemplifies the mutual support and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">commitment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of each country to ensuring </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">operationally independent, effective, safe and secure nuclear deterrence. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Building on more than fifty years of extremely close cooperation in our nuclear programmes, we are exploring opportunities for further collaboration. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:center; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Wider Security Issues</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="66" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The threats we face today require a much broader security relationship.  Central to protecting the people of our countries, and their prosperity, is our unique and indispensible relationship with the United States in the fields of intelligence, cyber, and counter terrorism.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Intelligence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Relationship</span></p><ol start="67" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For the UK and its intelligence agencies (GCHQ, SIS and MI5), the intelligence and security relationship with the US </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is very close</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is one in which both the UK and US rely on and benefit from to protect their national security. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Following allegations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">about intelligence gathering </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in early June, the UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">US intelligence relationship has come under intense scrutiny.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The Foreign Secretary made a statement to the House of Commons on 10 June on the work of the Government Communications Headquarters and its legal framework. In his statement the Foreign Secretary said that:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Since the 1940s GCHQ and its American equivalents, now the National Security Agency, have had a relationship that is unique in the world.  This relationship has been and remains essential to the security of both nations, has stopped many terrorist and espionage plots against this country, and has saved many lives.  The basic principles by which that cooperation operates have not changed over time. Indeed I wish to emphasise to the House that while we have experienced an extremely busy period in intelligence and diplomacy in the last three years, the arrangements for oversight and the general framework for exchanging information with the United States are the same as under previous Governments.  The growing and diffuse nature of threats from terrorists, criminals or espionage has only increased the importance of the intelligence relationship with the United States.  This was particularly the case in the run up to the Olympics.  The House will not be surprised that our activity to counter terrorism intensified and rose to a peak in the summer of last year</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.”</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="68" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Answering questions following the statement, the Foreign Secretary noted the ex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">panding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> importance of the UK’s close and unique cooperation with the United States. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Foreign Secretary strongly refuted suggestions that GCHQ uses its partnership with the United States to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">evade</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> UK law.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The Foreign Secretary was absolutely clear that this accusation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">was</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> baseless.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Indeed, following a thorough investigation, the Intelligence and Security Committee issued a statement on 17 July saying that the accusations were unfounded.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Cyber</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Security</span></p><ol start="69" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The US is a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">very significant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ally on cyber relations and we share mutual aims. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Prime Minister</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and President Obama signed a communiqué on cyber security in May 2011 which confirmed our shared </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">commitment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to international engagement, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">strengthening</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> rule of law, public private cooperation, capacity building, R&amp;D and continuing bilateral cooperation. Officials also regularly share information and coordinate cyber security work with other allies.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="70" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are compelling reasons for ensuring that the US and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">British</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overnments remain closely aligned on this issue. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our infrastructures are tightly coupled, and our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">most important</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ind</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ustry players are Transatlantic or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> multinational. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The dominance of US industry in internet service provision makes partnership with the US essential for the UK, and the UK's position as a global communications hub and as a major inward investor in critical infrastructure services in the US provides incentives for the US to engage with the UK as well. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">yber security is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> also</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> becoming an increasingly important component of overall security collaboration between our two countries. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are, ho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wever, countervailing pressures.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or example, our ICT sectors are intensely competitive, which makes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">companies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> nervous about sharing threat and vulnerability information widely. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n both countries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> data protection concerns may inhibit industry from sharing information with governments.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="71" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We cooperate closely on shared international objectives including building capacity in third countries to tackle cybercrime, online threats and to increase the resilience of cyberspace, as well as ensuring that cyberspace remains open to support economic and social development and the trust and innovation that underpin that.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="72" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are broadly aligned on Internet governance issues, with both the UK and the US in favour of maintaining the multi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stakeholder model of Internet governance (i.e. governments, business and civil society all having a role).  We coordinate well in international meetings on this to counter those, such as Russia and China, who want an increased role for governments and greater controls on the Internet in the name of state security at the expense of Freedom of Expression.   </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Counter Terrorism</span></p><ol start="73" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The counter terrorism relationship between the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">US</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is vital to t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he protection of UK i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nterests at home and overseas from the threat posed by Al </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Qae</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">da and allied terrorist groups, and for reducing the global threat of terrorism.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="74" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The US remain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> our most important counter terrorism partner, granting us privileged access to their intelligence and an openness in discussing common problems and approaches that does not apply to other countries.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">US counter terrorism relationship encompasses a wide spectrum of activity, including intelligence sharing and law enforcement, and is supported by an active </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dialogue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> at all levels across Government.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This collaboration is focussed on denying terrorist groups the space to operate, developing the capabilities of vulnerable countries and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">working to overcome</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the injustices terrorist </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">exploit and the ideologies that they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">deploy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="75" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In addition to our bilateral co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">operation we continue to work with the US through multilateral </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fora</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> including the Global Counter Terrorism Forum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which aims to mobili</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e expertise and resources to a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ddress and enhance global co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">operation on counter terrorism.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Building Stability</span></p><ol start="76" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The British Government is addressing instability and violent conflict overseas because it is both morally right and in Britain’s national interest.  Since the launch of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Building Stability Overseas Strategy, we have worked to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have an integrated approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">working </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">together </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">across our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">diplomatic, development, defence engagement and intelligence efforts.  We continue to work closely with the United States to establish common positions and approaches in those fragile and conflict-affected states which matter most to our shared interests, including Afghanistan, Pakistan, Somalia and Libya (see “Working Together on Foreign Policy Priorities”, above).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="77" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Stabilisation Unit (SU) has worked closely with its counterpart, the US Bureau for Conflict &amp; Stabilisation Operations (CSO)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> since our inception as the Post-Conflict Reconstruction Unit in 2004. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have previously seconded staff to CSO, and are currently hosting a US </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">secondee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> within the SU. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our relationship </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">supports</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> greater collaboration and coordination between SU and CSO activities in high priority fragile and conflict affected states, as well as enabling best practice and lessons learnt in facilitating integrated approaches to stabilisation to be shared. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We also identify evidence of ‘what works’ in a range of conflict and stabilisation contexts, and have shared lessons as to how to maintain and deploy appropriate capability to respond to current and future crises. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Together we co-host a six-monthly Stabilisation Leaders Forum involving Stabilisation Unit equivalents from UK, US, Canada, Australia, the Netherlands and Germany to discuss best practice and lessons learned across the operational conflict and stabilisation spectrum.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Extradition</span></p><ol start="78" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK has strong ex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tradition relations with the US</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  Effective extradition processes between the two countries are crucial to fighting cross-border crime.  The Home Secretary has made it clear that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the Government believes the UK-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">US Extradition Treaty is fair and balanced. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The US has never refuse</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d to extradite anyone to the UK, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has complied with requests received from the UK, and has extradited its citizens to the UK.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">New forum provisions were introduced in April 2013 to ensure that the possibility of a domestic prosecution has been properly explored as part of the extradition proceedings.  These allow a judge to bar extradition, on forum grounds, if the extradition would not be in the interests of justice.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Shared Prosperity</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 19.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="80" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">US trade and investment relationship continues to develop and prosper. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The US is the UK’s largest export destination, and we are the US</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> largest trading partner in the EU.  In 2011, UK-US trade in goods and services accounted for £129 billion in total.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK and the US also continue to be largest foreign investors in each other’s economies: over £400 billion (£204 billion of US investment in the UK; £210 billion of UK investment in the US in 2011).  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership</span></p><ol start="81" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Creating the conditions for a global economic recovery and stimulating jobs and growth for the UK remains the Government’s top priority. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The launch at the G8 Summit in Lough Erne </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of negotiations towards an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> EU/US Transatlantic Trade and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Investment Partnership </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(TTIP) could represent a step change in the US-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK trade relationship. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The principal benefits from an EU trade deal with the US are expected to come from improving the coherence between US and EU regulatory systems, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in order to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> eliminate unnecessary rules, differing standards for goods and different approval processes. Eliminating tariffs on goods could also save UK exporters almost £1 billion. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Overall, a comprehensive deal could be worth up to £10 billion (0.35% of GDP) to the UK economy, and £80 billion (0.4% of GDP) for the US.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="82" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> British</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Embassy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in Washington</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has commission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a study examining the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">impact</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of TT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IP on jobs and exports in the fifty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> US states.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The Embassy and the US </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">N</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">etwork will use this data to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> seek to generate support at both Congressional and state </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">level </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for the agreement. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> After the official launch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the data will be shared with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">European </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Commission and other Members States</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="83" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The negotiations are in their initial stages.  We will have significant interest in achieving liberalisation of the procurement market in the US, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bringing about</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> increased regulatory coherence in the financial services sector and securing tariff reductions in sectors such as automo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  Such a comprehensive agreement will be challenging, in particular in areas such as procurement where there is state-level competence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and also in agriculture.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Climate and Energy</span></p><ol start="84" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK objectives in our energy and climate work with the US are to achieve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a global deal that l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">imits global temperature rise to 2 degrees, to reduce emissions, to strengthen energy governance and to open energy markets. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="85" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Multilaterally we work through the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change, the Major Economies Forum, the International Energy Agency, Clean Energy Ministerial, the Carbon Sequestration Leadership Forum, the International Energy Forum, the Climate and Clean Air Coalition to Reduce Short-Lived Climate Pollutants and on climate finance.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Bilaterally we work closely with the US where we have a shared </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, where we feel we can learn from each others’ experience and where we need to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">promote</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">protect UK companies active in the US. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This includes specific work to learn lessons from the US shale gas experience, where we have benefited from US Government reports and first hand information from regulators, industry and other interest groups in Washington, Houston and Pennsylvania. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It also includes discussions on climate change, where in June this year, the Foreign Secretary and Secretary of State John Kerry met and discussed climate change including efforts to shape conditions and remove obstacles towards a 2015 agreement. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="86" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We also engage with s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tates, businesses and thought leaders as well as the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ederal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overnment and seek to support Science and Innovation Network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and UK Trade and Investment objectives in the area of our carbon policies, regulation and technology.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 19.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Working </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Through Our Network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> to Achieve Our Objectives</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="87" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In addition to our Embassy in Washington, the UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Consulates General in Boston, New York, Miami, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Houston, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Atlanta, Chicago, Denver, Los Angeles, and San Francisco.  We have one Consulate in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Orlando</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (devoted entirely to consular </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">issues), and a UK Government Office was opened in Seattle in January 2013 to promote business</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, economic, and political ties with Washington State.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-27.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="88" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This network of posts is the platform from which HMG pursues UK objectives in the US.  They promote trade and investment, foster science and innovation, and provide consular support to British citizens throughout the country.  They also build relationships with local political, business, and other leaders, from governors and mayors, to CEOs and university vice-chancellors.  Many </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">important </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">political figures in Washington cut their teeth in local politics, and the close relationships built up in these early years can prove invaluable.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 19.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Staffing across the US Network</span></p><ol start="89" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.88pt; padding-left:5.47pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">taffing of the US Network is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">set out in the table below, with comparative figures for our Networks in the EU, India and China. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 19.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:13.8pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0